  <exercises>

    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Determine the solution set to each equation or inequality.  Express the solution sets to the inequalities using interval notation (where possible).
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>4-\abs{x} \ge -11</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by isolating the absolute value expression.
            <md>
              <mrow>4-\abs{x} \amp\ge -11</mrow>
              <mrow>4-\abs{x}\subtractright{4} \amp\ge -11\subtractright{4}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\abs{x} \amp\ge -15</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{-1}-\abs{x} \amp\le \multiplyleft{-1}-15</mrow>
              <mrow>\abs{x} \amp\le 15</mrow>
            </md>
            We now write an equivalent compound inequality that does not include an absolute value expression.
            <me>-15 \le x \le 15</me>
            The solution set to the given inequality is <m>[-15, 15]</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>-3+\abs{5-x}=-2</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by isolating the absolute value expression.
            <md>
              <mrow>-3+\abs{5-x}\amp=-2</mrow>
              <mrow>-3+\abs{5-x}\addright{3}\amp=-2\addright{3}</mrow>
              <mrow>\abs{5-x}=1</mrow>
            </md>
            We now write a pair of equivalent equations that do not include absolute value expressions and go on to solve that pair of equations.
            <md>
              <mrow>5-x\amp=-1 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5-x\amp=1</mrow>
              <mrow>5-x\subtractright{5}\amp=-1\subtractright{5} \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 5-x\subtractright{5}\amp=1\subtractright{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>-x\amp=-6 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-4</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{-1}-x\amp=\multiplyleft{-1}-6 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp \multiplyleft{-1}-x\amp=\multiplyleft{-1}-4</mrow>
              <mrow>x\amp=6 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=4</mrow>
            </md>
            The solution set is <m>\{4,6\}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>2\abs{\frac{x}{3}}-12 \le -6</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by isolating the absolute value expression.
            <md>
              <mrow>2\abs{\frac{x}{3}}-12 \amp\le -6</mrow>
              <mrow>2\abs{\frac{x}{3}}-12\addright{12} \amp\le -6\addright{12}</mrow>
              <mrow>2\abs{\frac{x}{3}} \amp\le 6</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{2\abs{\frac{x}{3}}}{2} \amp\le \divideunder{6}{2}</mrow>
              <mrow>\abs{\frac{x}{3}} \amp\le 3</mrow>
            </md>
            We now write and solve an equivalent compound equality that does not include an absolute value expression.
            <md alignment="alignat">
              <mrow>-3 \amp\le \frac{x}{3} \amp \amp\le 3</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}-3 \amp\le \multiplyleft{3}\frac{x}{3} \amp \amp\le \multiplyleft{3}3</mrow>
              <mrow>-9 \amp\le x \amp \amp\le 9</mrow>
            </md>
            The solution set to the given inequality is <m>[-9,9]</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>5-6\abs{2x+1}=17</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by isolating the absolute value expression.
            <md>
              <mrow>5-6\abs{2x+1}\amp=17</mrow>
              <mrow>5-6\abs{2x+1}\subtractright{5}\amp=17\subtractright{5}</mrow>
              <mrow>-6\abs{2x+1}\amp=12</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{-6\abs{2x+1}}{-6}\amp=\divideunder{12}{-6}</mrow>
              <mrow>\abs{2x+1}\amp=-2</mrow>
            </md>
            We observe that there are no numbers whose absolute value is <m>-2</m> and conclude that the given equation has no solutions.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>30-\frac{\abs{x+9}}{5} \gt -40</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by isolating the absolute value expression.
            <md>
              <mrow>30-\frac{\abs{x+9}}{5} \amp\gt -40</mrow>
              <mrow>30 -\frac{\abs{x+9}}{5}\subtractright{30} \amp\gt -40\subtractright{30}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\frac{\abs{x+9}}{5} \amp\gt -70</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{-5}-\frac{\abs{x+9}}{5} \amp\lt \multiplyleft{-5}-70</mrow>
              <mrow>\abs{x+9} \amp\lt 350</mrow>
            </md>
            We now write and solve an equivalent compound inequality that does not include an absolute value expression.
            <md alignment="alignat">
              <mrow>-350 \amp\lt x+9 \amp\amp\lt 350</mrow>
              <mrow>-350\subtractright{9} \amp\lt x+9\subtractright{9} \amp\amp\lt 350\subtractright{9}</mrow>
              <mrow>-359 \amp\lt x \amp\amp\lt 341</mrow>
            </md>
            The solution set is <m>(-359,341)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>-\abs{\frac{8-2x}{3}}+15 \le 12</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We begin by isolating the absolute value expression.
            <md>
              <mrow>-\abs{\frac{8-2x}{3}}+15 \amp\le 12</mrow>
              <mrow>-\abs{\frac{8-2x}{3}}+15\subtractright{15} \amp\le 12\subtractright{15}</mrow>
              <mrow>-\abs{\frac{8-2x}{3}} \amp\le -3</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{-1}-\abs{\frac{8-2x}{3}} \amp\ge \multiplyleft{-1}-3</mrow>
              <mrow>\abs{\frac{8-2x}{3}} \amp\ge 3</mrow>
            </md>
            We now write and solve an equivalent compound inequality that does not include an absolute value expression
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{8-2x}{3} \amp\le -3 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp \frac{8-2x}{3} \amp\ge 3</mrow>
              <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}\frac{8-2x}{3} \amp\le \multiplyleft{3}-3 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp \multiplyleft{3}\frac{8-2x}{3} \amp\ge \multiplyleft{3}3</mrow>
              <mrow>8-2x \amp\le -9 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 8-2x \amp\ge 9</mrow>
              <mrow>8-2x\subtractright{8} \amp\le -9\subtractright{8} \amp\amp\text{or}\amp 8-2x\subtractright{8} \amp\ge 9\subtractright{8}</mrow>
              <mrow>-2x \amp\le -17 \amp\amp\text{or}\amp -2x \amp\ge 1</mrow>
              <mrow>\divideunder{-2x}{-2} \amp\ge \divideunder{-17}{-2} \amp\amp\text{or}\amp \divideunder{-2x}{-2} \amp\le \divideunder{1}{-2}</mrow>
              <mrow>x \amp\ge \frac{17}{2} \amp\amp\text{or}\amp x \amp\le -\frac{1}{2}</mrow>
            </md>
            The solution set to the given inequality is <m>\left(-\infty,-\frac{1}{2}\right] \cup \left[\frac{17}{2},\infty\right)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</section>
